  "id": "019d3282-2779-76a1-a65b-be3173506d93",
  "content": "# corvia-adapter-agent-teams: Detailed Design Exploration\n\n**Date:** 2026-03-28\n**Status:** Exploration\n**Doc:** docs/decisions/2026-03-28-adapter-agent-teams-exploration.md\n\n## Key Design Decisions\n\n### Relationship to claude-sessions adapter\nThe agent-teams adapter captures coordination state (tasks, messages, team structure). The claude-sessions adapter captures session content (turns, tool calls). They are complementary. Combined, they give full observability of what each teammate did AND how they coordinated.\n\n### Build approach: Extend claude-sessions (recommended)\nStart by extending the claude-sessions adapter with a `--domain agent-teams` mode rather than building a standalone binary. The data sources are closely related, graph edges need to cross-reference session IDs, and promotion logic is identical. Split later if complexity warrants.\n\n### Data sources\n- `~/.claude/teams/{team-name}/config.json` (team structure, members, roles)\n- `~/.claude/teams/{team-name}/inboxes/{agent-name}.json` (inter-agent messages)\n- `~/.claude/tasks/{team-name}/*.json` (tasks with status, ownership, dependencies)\n\n### Graph integration\nCreates edges connecting team -> members, tasks -> owners, task -> task (deps). Correlates agent_id from team config with session_id from session logs to bridge team coordination with session content.\n\n### Trigger: Hybrid approach\nHooks capture incrementally during team lifetime (TaskCompleted, TeammateIdle). Scan pass at ingest time catches anything hooks missed. Matches claude-sessions pattern.\n\n### Strategic positioning\nDistribution play: every Agent Teams user gets immediate corvia value. Defensive play: establishes corvia as the team memory layer before Anthropic builds one natively.\n\n## Open Questions\n1. File watching vs. scan (team files deleted on cleanup)\n2. Agent ID to session ID correlation reliability\n3. Incremental capture via TaskCompleted hook feasibility\n4. Message volume chunking for large teams\n5. Nested subagent attribution within teams\n",
